name: Condo in Amsterdam · ★5.0 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The Dapper neighborhood in Amsterdam is a fantastic destination for tourists who are looking to experience the city's authentic lifestyle. Located in the eastern part of the city, this colorful and vibrant neighborhood offers a wide range of attractions and activities for visitors of all ages and interests.

One of the most popular attractions in the Dapper neighborhood is the famous Dapper Market, which has been held on the streets of the neighborhood since 1910. The market offers an abundance of fresh produce, flowers, clothing, artwork, and much more. It's the perfect place to soak up the local atmosphere, haggle with vendors, and sample delicious food and drinks.

For visitors interested in the history of the Dapper neighborhood, the Tropenmuseum is a must-visit destination. This museum is dedicated to the cultural diversity of the world and boasts an extensive collection of ethnographic art objects, photography, musical instruments, films, and more.

If you prefer taking public transport: many trams depart from small distance of the house. Also only 15 minutes from Central Station.

There is a vast array of shopping opportunities, from fashion brands and chains (Nieuwendijk, Kalverstraat) through to independent innovators and inspiring market stalls, such as at Noordermarkt. - We're located 1.2 km from the historical area Jordaan with its' canals.

- Amsterdam Central Station is 2.1 km away.
- Schiphol Airport Amsterdam is 12 km away.
host_about:
We are conscious about the choices we make. That is why there is sustainability in everything that we do, without compromising comfort. And our stylish hotels and restaurants each have their own unique style and story, which makes every visit a special experience. We do it differently by nature.

We have been around for over 10 years now, making us pioneers in eco-friendly tourism.

We do it differently by combining stylish design and playfulness with sustainability, calling it Eco-Sexy. This is felt throughout your entire stay. From small notes in the rooms that tell guests about the recycled furniture and water-saving showers to every bite and drink that are served being fully organic. name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath

neighborhood_overview:
You will be in the very heart of the Jordaan, a neighbourhood lively with cafes, restaurants and bars.
You will be 5 minutes away on foot from the Prinsengracht and Anne Frank House, and about 2 from the trams and buses taking you to the museums (10 min) and the central station (5 min). That's if you don't prefer to just wander around on foot, around the practically car-free neighbourhood. Despite being one of the nicest areas of the city, the Jordaan is not overcrowded with tourists, which makes it the best place to enjoy the real Amsterdam feeling.

The best apple pie of Amsterdam is just at the end of the street (see winkel43.nl), together with the cosiest cafes and restaurants around. You will love the Saturday market with the best organic food and flea market opportunities, and the traditional Monday market, just in front of the door.

name: Boat in Amsterdam · ★5.0 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The Eastern Docklands neighborhood in Amsterdam is a beautiful area with many great features. Here are some things that make it a nice place to live or visit:

Waterfront Views:
The neighborhood is located right on the water, providing stunning views of the harbor and the IJ river.
Architecture:
The Eastern Docklands features modern architecture and design, making it a unique and stylish place to live or visit. There are also plenty of historic buildings and landmarks to explore, such as the KNSM Island and the Lloyd Hotel.
Green Spaces:
Despite being an urban area, the Eastern Docklands also has several parks and green spaces, including the Flevopark and the Oosterpark.
Cultural Attractions:
The neighborhood is home to a variety of cultural attractions, such as the Muziekgebouw aan 't IJ concert hall, the National Maritime Museum, and the Scheepvaartmuseum.

In my house I offer two double bed & coffee rooms each with a private shower and one room even with a bath. I live in the building and I have my own bathroom. A bed & coffee room means your rent a b&b room, but instead of breakfast with unlimited coffee and tea that you make with your own Nespresso maker. The building offers a pretty unique large roof terrace that is magically lit by night. 

I'm a foody and spend much of my time cooking, going to the local markets and enjoy restaurants. If you need some advise where to go or what to eat please ask!

In my home I offer my guests privacy. But please knock my door for questions or a chat any time and most likely we’ll meet on the terrace anyway ;)

Enjoying a city like Amsterdam is all about having a place where you feel comfortable and safe at home in a strange environment. And especially to have a good bed, a warm shower and a nice cup of coffee or tea with a stroopwafel at any time you like. In my travels I visit and visited a lot of B&B's globally. Staying in a room in somebody’s home often felt I was staying with friends. Some of them became and still are dear friends after many years. This experience is what I try to offer my guests. Live like a local, feel at home. Tot ziens in Amsterdam, Marcel.

B&B Lisenced by council of Amsterdam.

Kia ora

neighborhood_overview:
Our apartment is located on "centrumeiland" which is the newest part of Ijburg Amsterdam.
Ijburg is a beautiful neighbourhood at the edge of Amsterdam. Being right at the water of the IJmeer lake makes it a special get away from the touristy centre. Life on Ijburg is a little slower, very modern and connected to nature.

A land of wind and water, IJburg is Amsterdam's newest neighbourhood, made up of four man-made islands, with even more in development. Located in the easternmost part of the city, this up-and-coming area has quickly become popular among those who love modern architecture and water sports. Locals frequent the charming neighbourhood cafes and higher-end bars clustering around the yacht haven, whilst windsurfers, swimmers and beach goers head straight to Strand Blijburg for the spectacular sunsets and windswept views.

However it's important to note that our part of Ijburg is still under construction and you do get quite a bit of a building side

It’s criss-crossed with commercial streets, including Overtoom which has become a major interiors boulevard. And to attest to the area’s child-friendliness, the Bosboom Toussaintstraat with its many children-oriented stores is referred to as ‘Amsterdam’s delivery room’.

Boasting 178 nationalities, Oud West is multicultural but is pretty much free of the stereotypes that come with that.

neighborhood_overview:
This apartment is located in the "Hoofddorpplein" neighbourhood, which is located in the district "Amsterdam-Zuid".

The neighborhood was built in the twenties. The characteristic architectural style can be found everywhere in the streetscape, such as the eccentric housing porticoes and the pointed corner towers.

Two beautiful parks, Vondelpark and Rembrandtpark, are just around the corner: 5 minutes by bike or 15 minutes walk.
In the summer, you can relax (and even swim!) at the Stadiongracht or in Park Schinkeleilanden.

This quiet neighborhood is popular with families, students and couples. It is very conveniently located near the station Amsterdam-Zuid where all train, metro, and tram connections are available. Also the neighborhood is surrounded by the A10 so you will be on the highways in no time. Schiphol Airport is only at 10 minutes from the apartment by car.

J'espère que vous aimerez autant que moi cette jolie capitale au caractère si atypique.. Bon séjour à Amsterdam !

neighborhood_overview: Generator Amsterdam is perfectly placed between Centrum and Oost boroughs, providing views of the Oosterpark’s scenic English garden right next door. From our budget hotel in Amsterdam it couldn’t be easier to get out and about; there’s ample public transport nearby to put you among the museums, music, nightlife and culture on offer in every corner.
host_about: Generator Amsterdam is located in the up-and-coming eastern side of the city, overlooking Oosterpark. This former zoological university building can accommodate 564 guests in 168 twin and quadruple rooms, with en-suite bathrooms and incredible views of the surrounding area. There is also one luxury apartment for six people, with views of the park and a self-catered kitchen. It has flexible and spacious social areas, filled with creative design touches like glass-fronted elevators, a light and airy café and an outdoor terrace. We’ve turned the former lecture hall into an impressive chill-out lounge and bar, while the old library is now a relaxation and private events room. The basement and café are now dining destinations and the original boiler room has become a secret late night bar.

neighborhood_overview: Situated between the bustling Leidseplein - at the center of the theater district - and the serene Leidsegracht; considered to be the most picturesque canal in Amsterdam.  For centuries Leidseplein (est. 1660) was one of the main entrances to the City and the Leidsegracht dates back to 1612. This historically vibrant entertainment area offers a rich choice in bars and restaurants and is a 5 min walk to the Vondelpark and a 10 min walk to the Museum Quarter. Centrally located there are excellent public transport connections; also to Schiphol Airport (35 minutes) and Central Station (20 minutes).

The neighborhood we live in is called ‘Bos en Lommer’, also known as BOLO. Our place lies in a wonderfully quiet street, but rush and entertainment is close!

For (sports) relaxation, a playground or a cup of coffee at Café Terrasmus you can easily walk to the Erasmuspark, which is just nearby. Another great coffeeplace is ‘Bagels & Beans’, located on the Bos en Lommerweg.

This is also the street for daily shopping. You will find three supermarkets here (two of them open till 22:00, seven days a week). Next to that you have a lot of African, Marrocan and Turkisch stores just across the street.

For breakfast, lunch and dinner, you have a lot to choose: Buurman & Buurman (great terrace and pizza’s), Spaghetteria (for fresh pasta) and Mas Mais (for Mexican tacos and great cocktails) are a few options. Don’t forget to get some fries from ‘Friterie Zwagers’ located at the cross road of Erasmusgracht and Hoofdweg! A tiny little kiosk where you can buy snack

Previously this area was a bit of a wasteland, now the disused warehouses host creative start-ups, festivals, restaurants and, once a month, mega flea market. We name: The Eye Film Museum (10 minutes by bicycle), trendy restaurants like Pllek, Noorderlicht, de IJkantine and Hotel de Goudfazant and little cosy and affordable places like De Soepboer, Thai restaurant Pasoek and Italian restaurant San Remo.
Up north only 5 kilometers far away you will find yourself in the typical Dutch countryside called Waterland with beautiful authentic villages like Monnickendam, Broek in Waterland, Marken and Volendam. Open air museum de Zaanse Schans is only 10 kilometers away. It shows the way of living in the Netherlands during the last centuries in authentic buildings and windmills.

host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel Amsterdam is a place where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

name: Guest suite in Amsterdam · ★4.91 · Studio · 1 bed · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: Central located in Amsterdam with all the great musea in the backyard.
host_about:
Hi, 

Nice to virtually meet you and thanks for taking the time to read a little something about me, before or after booking one of my studios!:)

My name is Ellen, I am 46 years old (2021) and I recently renovated my double floor apartment in Amsterdam. This was the biggest (construction) project of my live and I enjoyed every single step of this proces. 

Due to the total renovation I was able to create two fully equipped private studio’s, which I’ve designed with a lot of love and attention. I thought it through over and over again, chose colors, materials and furniture as if I was going to live there myself. And I actually did in the studio on the top floor, while my house on the first floor was totally stripped and build up again. Because I totally stripped both floors and the attic, it was possible for me to change the entrance doors. So the studios are now connected to my private house, but with a private entrance as well as a private bathroom and a private kitchen. Meaning that you don’t have to see me, if you don’t want to!:) You are always welcome to say ‘hello’ and to take a look at my place. 

The entrance to my house is on the first floor and that’s where I live together with my cat "Pietertje” and my dachshund “Willem”. Those two boys are really giving me a lot of joy, love and fun in my live. They are definitely the best roommates ever!;) I had a fosterchild living with me every other weekend and in the beginning of this year fulltime. She turned 18 last september, so now she is living her life as a ‘free’ young adult. I am still in contact with her and I really hope that I can follow her adult steps because she allows me to. It’s a new way of living together apart and I’m curious how the relationship between the two of us evolves towards the future.  

As a professional I work as a freelance change manager, mainly for Dutch television companies. I really love my job and I always seem to get these perfect matching assignments, which give me positive energy. Off course sometimes I feel the opposite, but fortunately 90% of my professional time spent is vibrant. Since I worked for Dutch television since I was 25 years old,  in many different roles and finally as Director Operations, this is a business which is running through my veins. I like the atmosphere and the content, so I hope to stay in this business as long as I like it. 

Besides these assignments I’m studying at the Dutch Academy for Psychotherapy to become an Integrative Therapist. I’m in my second year now, so already graduated as a certified coach. I’m still figuring out what I’m going to do exactly with this expertise. What will be the form that suits me best? I don’t have the answers yet, but I’m sure it will all come to me as I take it step by step and dare to trust in myself and the future. 

If I’m not working or studying, I like to explore Amsterdam with myself or with friends. There is always something new to discover. There is actually a whole cultural side of Amsterdam which is an unknown area for me and I really want to explore that part of the city. I experienced that my personal interests changes over the years and because of these changes in time, I realize that I can learn and discover more and more about my city every single year. That’s probably one of the fun things of living life!:)

I really hope to welcome you in one of my studio’s and I would be very pleased to make sure you can enjoy a carefree stay in Amsterdam. 

Please do not hesitate and contact me if you have any questions or if you want any personal favorites according to restaurants, bars and other hotspots.

All the best and maybe see you soon!

Ellen

We are a Dutch - Colombian family, living in the centre of Amsterdam, the Netherlands. We enjoy traveling as well as hosting friends and family coming from abroad.

During our own vacations we like to let other people enjoy Amsterdam and our apartment. For that reason, we often rent out our apartment when we’re away. We lived here for ~15 years so we can provide many tips and tricks to enjoy Amsterdam like a local. 

In terms of destinations of our own vacations, we often go to Gstaad, Switzerland, to enjoy nature, sports, some relaxation, and quality time with family & friends. The region has so much to offer throughout the year! We always go to chalet Les Cèdres, which we also happen to rent out.

neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam East is one of the upcoming or so called hipster neighbourhoods in Amsterdam! It seems that a new hotspot pops up almost every day in this neighbourhood. The neighbourhood is only a short bicycle drive away from the city centre, but has such a different vibe. i.e.: Have a drink at the rooftop bar of the Volkshotel and enjoy the stunning views over Amsterdam.

When it comes to restaurants there is something for everyone in Amsterdam East. From trendy coffee bars, industrial warehouses, cocktail bars to concept stores! The Czaar Peter Street and the Javastraat are some of the best shopping streets on the East side of town. All kinds of trendy shops can be found here.

On a sunny day it’s definitely a must to visit 'Roest' for a drink on the waterside. If you want the local feel and multi-culti you can visit the Dappermarket with all its vedors or visit the Oosterpark. The renewed Beukenplein is perfect for a drink afterwards!

The Jordaan is a district in the citycenter of Amsterdam, known for its beautiful houses, nice restaurants and original shops. When in Amsterdam, it is a must to stroll through the little streets and canals. Popular streets in the Jordaan are the Prinsengracht, the Westerstraat, Haarlemmerstraat and the '9 straatjes' (nine little streets).

name: Home in Amsterdam · ★4.75 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The Tuindorp-Oostzaan neighborhood truly has "the best of both worlds". The bustling NDSM with its street art, art studios, fun bars and flea markets is just around the corner (5 to 10 min). Here you also take the ferry to the center within 10 min. So if you like, you are right in the buzz of the city, but on the other hand you can also get a breath of fresh air in the Twiske nature reserve. Enjoy a typical Dutch rural view with windmills. You can enjoy hiking and swimming in the summer.

Furthermore, our house is not far from the ring road and you can park for free. One of the few places in Amsterdam where that is still possible. The bus also stops in front of the door and has a good connection to Schiphol Airport and Central Station.

name: Condo in Amsterdam · ★4.91 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The house is in the 'Indische Buurt' In Amsterdam East, a vibrant multicultural area.

Dappermarkt is one of the country’s oldest - and best - outdoor markets. It forms the multicultural heart of the neighbourhood along with such major arteries as Javastraat, which once only provided every manner of global grocery but is now beginning to feature more upscale cafes and terraces.

Two stellar city parks, Oosterpark and Flevopark, provide quick escape from the relatively busy streets.

Besides many cheap ethnic eateries and supermarkets, the area is attracting much more higher-end cafes and restaurants who are often re-inventing many of the area’s industrial monuments. On sunny days, the parks resemble impressionist painting depicting feasting locals. And who can knock a brewery, Brouwerij ’t IJ, who have a bona fide windmill from under which you can enjoy their brews? name: Home in Amsterdam · ★5.0 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam Oud West is a lively and bustling neighborhood with lots of charm and various attractions. There are several reasons why people enjoy visiting this neighborhood. Here are some of the highlights:

Cultural diversity: Amsterdam Old West is a melting pot of different cultures. You will find a mix of people, restaurants and shops from all over the world. This creates a lively and cosmopolitan atmosphere.

The Jordaan: Oud West borders the popular Jordaan district, which is known for its picturesque streets, cozy cafes and brown bars. It is a great place to walk, shop and enjoy the Amsterdam atmosphere.

Food scene: Amsterdam Oud West has a thriving food scene with a wide variety of restaurants, cafes and eateries. Whether you're looking for traditional Dutch dishes, exotic street food or trendy brunch spots, you're sure to find something to suit your taste here.

neighborhood_overview:
Since your hotel room is in the middle of Amsterdam Center, many must-sees are within walking distance: the Maritime Museum, NEMO Science Museum, the Skinny Bridge, the Hermitage, the vintage market on Waterlooplein… the possibilities are endless. Bookings for bridge house Hortusbrug include a SWEET little extra for plant lovers: free entrance to the beautiful ‘Hortus Botanicus’ next-door. Complete your nature and history-themed day with a visit to Artis Zoo at just a 6-minute walk. Check out our self-composed Neighbourhood Guide on the tablet in the room for more recommendations!

This bridge house is classed as NOISE LEVEL - MEDIUM.
host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.75 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
host_about:
I am originally from Asia, but I consider myself a cultural nomad, since I have lived in and traveled to more than 100 countries. Believe me, it gets tired one day. And that is why I bought a house recently, to root me down, and to give me some sense of being homey. 

I am a freelance writer. When I am not writing, I teach and do research at the university. When I'm not writing or working at the university, I am probably lost somewhere in one of my new journeys. My way of traveling is to get in touch with the authentic life as much as I possibly can, so I often stay with local families, in local houses, and shun the hotels all together. 

From all my journeys, the country where I would want to come back for food is Peru, for culture is India, for nature is New Zealand, for people is Yemen, and for a deep touch of love, I go to Vietnam. My dream is to be able to visit Saudi Arabia because it is the only place that does not welcome normal tourists. However, the two places where I seem to have everything right now are Sydney, and of course Amsterdam. It is a greedy combination I know. As a consequence, I often manage to live in Sydney several months each year. 

I have been with Airbnb for a while, but I still have a lot to learn. I would appreciate it if you can tell me what I should do to make your stay here a great experience.

The Hoofddorpplein neighborhood is very wanted amongst people from Amsterdam to live, because it’s not busy, but has enough shops, restaurants and cafes, and still is close to the center and almost feels like a little village inside the city. Within a 20 minutes walk through the Vondelpark you will find popular sites such as the Rijksmuseum, the Van Gogh Museum, the Royal Concerthall and the Leidseplein.
Enjoy Amsterdam to the fullest! Let me know what time you’ll arrive and I’ll be there to check you in. Of course you will be provided with fresh bed linen and towels.

Mini Supermarket 1 minute walk, big supermarket 4 minutes walk.
Restaurants at a 5 minute walk as well as almost any other kind of shop.
Bike rental at a 10 minute walk.
host_about:
We are a family of five:  us two, our 3 daughters plus two cats. Working both full time and pretty hard, so always very much looking foreword to holiday time, which isn't that easy to finance when traveling the regular way, staying in hotels etc. Our friends are so enthusiastic about AirBnB that we decided to join as well. When you think of it, it's crazy everybody's traveling leaving their own houses empty, renting cold and standard apartments en hotel rooms all around the world. So here we are!
We both work in the hospitality business ( Dorian is a chef and I'm hospitality manager at one of the greatest Concert halls in the world, the Concertgebouw). So what we like is obvious maybe: cooking and spending time with our friends and neighbors. But also in our little free time, reading, gardening ( me), running in the Vondelpark ( Dorian), watching series on Netflix ( only since a few months available here) and of course going on trips with our children. Preferably by train. Besides we don't own a car, it's just such a great way to travel.

You can find many great little shops, good restaurants and typical bars in the neighborhood.

Every Monday morning, a textile market is held on the street, which extends to the famous fleemarket on the Noordermarkt. On Saturday, the fleemarket is smaller and gives way to lots of great organic food and produce stalls.

name: Home in Amsterdam · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1.5 baths
Condo in Amsterdam · ★4.67 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Stay in the heart of Amsterdam and experience how it is to live like a real 'Amsterdammer'. Step outside of the door and enjoy some of the most stunning views of the Amsterdam canals.

We love the neighbourhood with its museums, nice restaurants and bars. Around the corner you can enjoy the best brunch of Amsterdam at Bakers & Roasters, go for a beer and 'bitterballen' at Orloff, have some amazing wood-oven pizza at Sotto, enjoy delicious Indonesian food at Cafe Kadijk or go for a fancy high-end dinner at restaurant Entrepot. All within 50 meters from the apartment!

Although the neighbourhood is centrally located, it is known as a 'little village' in Amsterdam due to its quiet atmosphere and social people. If you want to really experience Amsterdam, there is no better place to stay.

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.90 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Oud Zuid is central: on one end you have Amsterdam’s nightlife and culture square Leidseplein and on the other Amstelveenseweg that is developing into a true culinary boulevard. And throughout the neighbourhood, a new bar seems to pop up every week. But for residents, firm favourites remain Vondelpark’s Vondelpark3 and Blauwe Theehuis. The Vondelpark remains Amsterdam’s most densely populated place-to-be whenever the sun shines. Besides this it’s nice to live near one of the greatest overviews of Western Art in the world. Two of the main museums, the Rijksmuseum and the Stedelijk Museum. For big shopping streets you can go to the PC Hooftstraat, Jacob Obrechtstraat, Cornelis Schuytstraat and Beethovenstraat.

Dam square: 4 km
Central station: 5 km
Museum square: 2,5 km
host_about:
We are Marten and Cindy from Amsterdam, love to sport, travel, discover other cultures and enjoy festivals once a while. Besides being a photographer, I (Cindy) love to paint, mainly caused by travelling. Marten works as a lawyer in Haarlem and is a creative writer in his spare time. 
In 2013 we experienced travelling and hosting with airbnb for the first time. We think it is very special; people open their house and make you feel at home. As a guest you respect and love this too? Then you can have such a beautiful experience. Because we like to meet other people and be of good service, this is a nice combination. 
We have a special interest in Spanish-language, same as the Spanish spoken countries, that for I (Cindy) worked as a volunteer and travelled for half a year in Latin-America.

p.s. Most of the time you will talk to me, but Dinah or Noehl is taking care of our apartment in Amsterdam, while I am gone!

For more peace and quiet there are also beautiful nature areas in the vicinity where you can also swim in natural water! By bike you can easily reach Amsterdamse Bos (10-15 min by bike) or Nieuwe Meer (10 min walk) The beach is within an hour travel by public transport and half an hour by car. Lovely alternative for days with sight seeing.

Welcome to my wonderful houseboat! I live here with my two children Rocco and Dante. You may have understood that I come from Italy! I left my hometown Venice and my "adopted city" Rome, spent 10 years traveling to different continents and finally I chose to move here in Netherlands five years ago, to try to make a change of my life. I have found a wonderful and exciting city that can give back a lot from hard work. In addition to the "cancer" like me who love sea, open spaces bright and clean but at the same time be able to find any stimulus from a dynamic and cosmopolitan city, I found the perfect place to continue my journey!

Benvenuti a tutti nella mia fantastica casa galleggiante! Vivo qui con i miei due bambini Rocco e Dante. Avrete forse capito che vengo dall'Italia! Ho lasciato la mia città natale Venezia e la mia "adottiva" Roma, passato 10 anni a viaggiare per diversi continenti e alla fine ho scelto di trasferirmi qui in Olanda 5 anni fa per cercare di dare una svolta alla  mia vità e ho trovato una città meravigliosa e stimolante che puo restituire molto dal duro lavoro. Inoltre per i "cancro" come me che amano il mare, gli spazi aperti, luminosi e puliti ma allo stesso tempo avere la possibilità di trovare qualunque stimolo da una città cosi dinamica e cosmopolita, ho trovato il luogo perfetto per continuare il mio viaggio!

neighborhood_overview: Amsterdam Noord has been transformed into Amsterdam’s edgiest and coolest neighbourhood. It’s a place that is constantly evolving and where there’s always a new hotspot drawing in crowds from all over the city. No place epitomises this as much as NDSM, a former wharf and hub of the shipbuilding hub that has undergone a rapid transformation. We take the five-minute ferry back to Amsterdam Centraal Station and then hop another one over to NDSM. As soon as we hit land, it’s visible just how rapid the pace of change is here. Construction is going on all around us. Read more: manvsglobe website online: amsterdam-noord-netherlands-coolest-hipster-offbeat/

name: Boat in Amsterdam · ★5.0 · 1 bedroom · 6 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The ship is moored in the marina of IJburg. Characteristic of IJburg is that it's located on an archipelago of artificial islands in the IJmeer. As a result, the ship is right next to (or should we say in) the IJmeer, and makes you simply a few minutes away from beautiful nature reserves. The swamp forest 'Diemer Vijfhoek' is a well-known one, where the alternation of wetlands, open water and reed lands make it a true bird paradise. You can walk here from the boat in 20 minutes.

Fort Island Pampus is a stone's throw from the venue. The ferry service to Pampus departed just around the corner.

Craving an adventure a bit more far away? Polder IJdoorn and Vuurtoreneiland are located slightly to the north of the location and can be reached via Zeeburg. Here you can walk beautifully and enjoy the unique flora & fauna.

Still looking for the crowds? Amsterdam is less than 20 minutes away.

name: Cottage in Amsterdam · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Our neighbourhood is very green, in a traditional old area and port: Nieuwendam. It only became part of Amsterdam after the floods of 1916. Amsterdam-Noord is now a renowned up and coming hotspot of Amsterdam, especially with the launch of the Metro (Noord-Zuidlijn) this summer. Very close (2 minutes walk) is the NIeuwendammerdijk with its characteristic wooden and stone houses and at a harbour by the water the lovely café restaurant, the Sluisje.

We leave our bikes (renting bikes costs 15-20 euros a day) and you are free to use these to explore also in the countryside just outside Amsterdam, into Waterland, Marken, Broek in Waterland, Ransdorp, Zunderdorp, Holysloot. We have 4 adult bikes, a (pink!) 9 year old's bike and a 12 year old's bike.

We have a preference for families / people traveling with parents or children or mature couples. This is a quiet neighbourhood, so not for people who want to party. As we often have friends visiting from overseas
host_about:
We are a pretty regular Dutch-English family with 4 rapidly growing up kids.  When not at home we love travelling, hiking, anything involving water and eating ice-cream!

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.19 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: De Pijp is vibrant and very much on its way up. As can be expected of an area that is centred on the nation’s most famous outdoor market: Albert Cuypmarkt, near to the Heineken brewery. This Amsterdam neighbourhood is famously diverse with over 100 nationalities represented. While still the best neighbourhood to choose from a wide selection of ethnic food, more high-end bars and restaurants have come on the scene to service students and young professionals. Further east along De Pijp there is the Van Woustraat, a former fast food strip, there are now several of the city’s more highly regarded restaurants. But perhaps most representative of the area is Bazar, a former church on the Albert Cuypmarkt that has been reinvented as a funky North African café/restaurant.

neighborhood_overview:
The Ark is located at the Weesperzijde one of the most special places near the Amstel which is according to many guest their favorite area of Amsterdam. This part is very popular because of its many different bars and restaurants and the nice atmosphere. Also the Weesperzijde is known for having the most sun hours a day in the city.

At the other side of the Amstel there is another popular part of the city, De Pijp – like Quartier Latin in Paris. There you will also find many lovely places to eat. From the residence you are able to go on a wounderful walk alongside the Amstel where you will pass many famous places such as the Stopera, Hermitage, Carre Theatre, Amstel Hotel and finally the Amstel Tower. Also you will pass by all kinds of popular terraces like the famous and typically Amsterdam, Cafe Hesp. Finally, if you would like to have some activity you will also have the opportunity to rent tennis gear or a kano.

name: Loft in Amsterdam · ★4.80 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This area in Amsterdam is one of the most upcoming neighbourhoods, with a large variety of interesting restaurants and bars, boutique shops showcasing the best of Amsterdam design (it would be difficult not to find an appropriate gift or unique souvenir). Within 100 meters we have the recently opened "De Hallen", which is an industrial building hosting a food plaza, great shops, art, a very good cinema called 'Filmhallen' and bars. It can be a bit crowded as it's the place to go at this moment in Amsterdam.

There are supermarkets (Albert Heijn, Dirk van den Broek, Marqt en Bilder en de Clerq) around the corner and the daily ‘Ten Kate market’ as well. If you prefer to walk to the center, it will take you about 10 minutes to the Jordaan, including the ‘9 straatjes’, the canals or 20 minutes to the Vondelpark or Westerpark (which we prefer over Vondelpark).

neighborhood_overview:
The Riekerpolder is a polder in the municipality of Amsterdam, district of Nieuw-West (before 1921 municipality of Sloten), north of the Nieuwe Meer.

The Riekerpolder is a continuation of the Rietwijkerpolder and the Bovenwegse Sloterpolder (or Sloterbuitenpolder) and was created in 1636 when the area between the Sloterweg and the Nieuwe Meer was diked and drained with a polder mill, the Riekermolen. The polder is part of a peat meadow area that was part of the Hollands-Utrecht peat area.

The pastureland thus created remained intact for centuries. During the reclamation of the Haarlemmermeer (1849-1852), a part of the polder in the southwest was excavated for the Ringvaart of the Haarlemmermeerpolder, between where Badhoevedorp and the hamlet of Nieuwe Meer are now located.

The Sieger Park has been located along the Sloterweg since the 1930s. There are also allotments ('Ons Buiten'), which have been established here since 1927, and there is the Sportpar

neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam is a relatively small city with an extensive offering of shopping, food, entertainment and culture. So, everyone has easy access to everything. There are not that many locations, however, where so much is reachable within minutes of walking. Our Town House is positioned in the middle of the Western canal area, a location that might be optimal in terms of access:

Nine streets
The ‘SOHO’ of Amsterdam, the ‘nine streets’, can be found in the side streets of the Keizersgracht at each side of the house. These streets hold many of Amsterdam’s interesting and fashionable stores (and restaurants), and on the weekends create a very pleasant buzz of people strolling around or sitting at the side walk cafes.

Jordaan
De Jordaan, generally considered the most picturesque of the Amsterdam neighbourhoods, and home to numerous restaurants, bars and small shops, starts one block away from the house.

host_about:
Hey,

Welcome to Amsterdam, my idea of a user-friendly city!

Amsterdam is a lovely place to spend a few days in, particularly if you will be able to dive in to the local rhythm of life. 
Living in the 400 year old canal belt of Amsterdam allows one a fairytale like feeling, its a bubble of village life in a middle of a very modern and vibrant city. And this is the exact sensation we want our guest to experience.

After a decade of living in Aruba, Dutch Caribbean, we moved back to NL and were fortunate enough to "land" on the Amstel. 
You're very welcome to enjoy this beautiful part of Amsterdam from a fully private apartment. 

Cheers!

name: Bed and breakfast in Amsterdam · ★New · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 private bath
neighborhood_overview: You'll stay in the city's most historic area, on a road with virtually no traffic. There is a sense of relative calm even though you'll be right in the city centre, opposite the original campus of the University of Amsterdam and a five-minute walk from the city's notorious Red Light district. Cafés & restaurants are around the corner, as is an art gallery, theatre, museum and one of Amsterdam's oldest canal tour companies, Rederij P. Kooij. Rokin Metro station, as well as a stop for buses and trams, are a two-minute walk away. And so is Amsterdam's main shopping street, leading to Dam Square and the city's most famous department store, De Bijenkorf.
host_about: Multi-lingual ex-diplomat, now working to make your stay easy, comfortable & memorable. My partner & I live in a stunning house built in 1655, on one of the nicest canals. Cafés & restaurants are around the corner, and just about all key attractions are a short walk or easy bike ride away. Welcome!

neighborhood_overview: The Amsterdam Oud-West district is one of the most lively and trendy areas of the city. Marqt, the best Dutch organic shop is just around the corner if you like to buy and cook the best fresh vegetables, meat and fish. name: Home in Amsterdam · ★4.93 · 1 bedroom · 6 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
'De Pijp' as we Amsterdammers know it today is without doubt a melting pot of cultures and nationalities. The Pijp is known for the vividness of it, and almost feels like a little village inside the city.

De Pijp is brimming with fantastic cafés, culinair restaurants, coffee shops and bars. Within walking distance from the apartment you will find popular sites such as the Heineken Museum, the Van Gogh Museum, Vondelpark, The Royal Concerthall, Paradiso, Leidseplein and the Rijksmuseum.The Albert Cuyp market (just round the corner) is the most famous day market in Amsterdam.

It will take about five minutes by foot to get to the center of Amsterdam. You will also be able to take the tram, stops are only a three minutes walk from the apartment. De Pijp is also known for it's shops, bars and muliticultural restaurants. The Sarphatipark and the Vondelpark are just around the corner.
We love the Pijp and already live here now for 22 years. It's not touristic but

host_about:
Welcome at Mi BnB, our B&B in Amsterdam West! We started in May 2017 and have had lots of guests from all over the world since then.

Mi BnB offers 2 simple rooms, the larger "Nice Room" on the 1st floor and the "Cozy Room" our tiny room on the ground floor. 

Each room has it's own small private bathroom, a smart tv,  coffee & tea facilities and a fridge. The 2 rooms share the front door and a small hall.

The B&B is in our family home in a nice, quiet, green neighbourhood, with excellent public transport around the corner. It is only half an hour to the city centre and all the tourist attractions are easy to reach by bus, tram or bike!

In Amsterdam it is only allowed to run a B&B when the owner lives in the house as well. So we are also living in the house with our children and our German Sheppard.

Please don't expect silence! At night it is quiet in general after 22h.

I love to meet new people from over the world and to speak foreign languages like English, Spanish, Italian and a little Portuguese, French and German.

We rent bikes for 10 euro per bike per day. 

Hope to meet you soon! 
Michèle  - Mi BnB

The neighborhood is located next to the beautiful Westerpark and the Westergasfabriek, where events are regularly organized, and where you can also relax or recreate in the summer. In addition, there are also many cozy restaurants and bars in and around the Westerpark to enjoy a bite to eat, drinks and entertainment.

There are several public transport stops spread throughout the district, for example to travel to Central Station in 5 minutes. From the Staatsliedenbuurt you are on the A10 (highway) in no time to easily travel to Haarlem, Zandvoort (beach) or Schiphol.

In addition you will find all sorts of other shops (H&M, Blokker) and restaurants, from cafes to KFC and McDonalds, or Asian takeaway.

name: Home in Amsterdam · ★5.0 · 5 bedrooms · 5 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview: Our neighbourhood is in the sunny side of the river IJ that crosses Amsterdam. Amsterdam's north side is undergoing a rapid transformation of gentrification where industry, varying from wharves to small scale car shops, is making place for houses. Our specific neighborhood has been residential since the early 20th century. Although in our street there are three older farms, one going back as far as the 17th century. It has a very cosy and private feeling, with many gardens, an old dyke, a canal and it still has a certain rural atmosphere. But as said before; Central Sation is 15 minutes by bike, from there on you easily walk or bike almost anywhere in Amsterdam since it is a very compact city. You can obviously also connect to almost all trains, trams, busses and metro.

neighborhood_overview: Oud West is close to the city-centre and close to both Vondelpark and Rembrandtpark. Ten Katestraat market is an excellent outdoor market with its charming cross-street ‘Bellamystraat’ giving the area an old-fashion village vibe – complete with dance studio and blacksmith. Kinkerstraat is a multicultural area with a large shopping street filled with bars, restaurants, clothes etc. It’s criss-crossed with commercial streets, including Overtoom which has become a major interiors boulevard. Two of the city’s more interesting alternative cultural complexes, OT301 and Lab111, which both mix music, film and art, are located here. But for a real taste for the relaxed diversity of this neighbourhood, visit the sprawling terrace of Du Cap to truly witness all walks of life. And again: the whole city is pretty much nearby.

neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood is very peaceful, safe and family-friendly. It has a bit of a village vibe inside a bigger city. The direct neighborhood is considered upscale, with lots of families with children living in the area.

There is a playground directly around the corner, with a picnic area and the possibility to swim in the dock during summer.

There is also a traditional Dutch snackbar (Febo), and a bike rental (Halfords) just around the corner and an outisde neighborhood (farmers') market every Wednesday, Friday and Saturday, called 'Pekmarkt'.

The market, and closest supermarket, grocery shops and stores are located at Mosveld, a 10-15 minute walk or a 3-4 minute bike ride.
The opening hours from the supermarket (Albert Heijn) are 7-22 and 8-22 during the weekend, also on Sunday!

It is very easy to get to the house from the Central Station.

Once you cross the IJ canal, it is 10-15 minute walk or 4 minute bike ride to the location

Artis, the famous zoo is very close too. Our area features mainly 1920's and 1930's construction and is very green. Beautiful parcs "Frankendael": 400 m. and "Oosterpark" 1400 m. Both great for walks or barbecues/picknicks.

If you want to go to the city center you just walk to the end of our street and hop on tram line 19 which will take you there in about 15 minutes.

name: Boat in Amsterdam · ★4.83 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Motoryacht Flint is located on a unique and beautiful location called 'Nieuwe Meer'. On the south side the lake borders on the Amsterdamse Bos. On the north side is the nature and recreation area De Oeverlanden. In about 25 minutes you can reach the centre of Amsterdam by public transport. You could say, the best of both worlds, staying in nature on the edge of the bustling city centre. Directly on the harbor is a restaurant with a large terrace that offers a beautiful view over the lake. Within walking distance of the harbor (1500 meters) you can rent bikes. Near the harbor you will find several supermarkets, which you can reach on foot but with the bike you can do your shopping faster. Within walking distance (12 minutes) is a large wellness resort where you can play squash, tennis or enjoy a lovely sauna. On the port area you can park your car for free during your stay.

If you would like more additional information, please do not hesitate to contact me.

I’m 38 years old and I live in Amsterdam for more than 10 years now. My boyfriend (Thomas) and I bought this totally renovated apartment 10 years ago. We love our house because of its central location and the nice view over the water of the Da Costakade. It feels like a private lake just in front of our door. When the sun comes out our garden-side balcony is the perfect place for a morning breakfast and coffee. And in the afternoon we often enjoy a glass of wine on our French balcony on the other side of the apartment, watching many boats come by on the canal. 
Last summer we discovered the Amsterdam canals with our own private boat. Being near the water or on the water is one of the most relaxing things you can do in this city (there’s a boat rental nearby if you would like to try).  We also enjoy cooking and dining at home or somewhere else in the city. If you are interested I can give you some nice tips for sightseeing, shopping, the best coffee place, bakery and dining places in the neighbourhood.

host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel Amsterdam is a place where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.85 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The B&B is located in the Jordaan, Amsterdam’s most popular city centre neighborhood. The Jordaan is popular for its trendy shops and cosy bars and restaurants and the famous Noordermarkt, which is a farmers-market and a flea-market on Saturday and on Monday. Originally a working-class neighborhood, the Jordaan has become one of the most expensive, upscale locations in the Netherlands. It is home to many galleries. Rembrandt spent his last years in the Jordaan. He was buried in the Westerkerk church behind the B&B.

Stepping out of our door you find yourself immediately in between the most beautiful part of the historical canals and next to Anne Frank Museum and the Wester Church. Amsterdam Central Station, the Dam square, Red Light District, China Town, the trendy '9 streets', the parks and all museums are all walking distance. You will find public transport, trams stops, tour boats and a taxi stop and also several bike rentals around the corner.
host_about: Hello, this is Robert from Amsterdam where I  offer a bedroom with en-suite private bathroom as a Bed & Coffee room. This means I don’t serve breakfast, but coffee and tea are included. This is the place where hipsters like to shop at one of the trendy boutiques, healthy food lovers can eat at one of the many organic cafes and on the weekends this is the neighbourhood to go out for drinks.

Being foodie’s paradise, the neighbourhood is home to almost 150 nationalities and the food choices certainly reflect this diversity. You will find a vast variety of authentic and exotic ethnic cuisine, such as Syrian, Moroccan, Surinamese, Turkish, Japanese, Spanish and more. Bar-ca takes you to Spain, while vegetarians find their fix at De Waaghals. North African, Moroccan and Turkish dishes dominate the Bazar; Cake shop Taart van mijn Tante satisfies the sweet cravings.

The Zeeheldenbuurt is a neighborhood in the Amsterdam district West , in the Dutch province of North Holland .

The neighborhood is located on both sides of the Westerkanaal , to the north of the Van Noordtgracht and the Zoutkeetsgracht and to the south of the Oude Houthaven . At the Zoutkeetsgracht the neighborhood borders the Western Islands , on the east side at the Westerdok and on the west side at the Spaarndammerbuurt . The Centrumring S100 crosses the neighborhood.

The neighborhood is sometimes confused with the younger and more westerly situated Admiralenbuurt and Mercatorbuurt, in the neighborhoods De Baarsjes and Bos en Lommer , where streets are named after admirals and explorers etc.

Locals and travellers alike come to catch some rays on our terrace, sticking around for an affordable dinner and some free cultural nourishment.
host_about:
BUNK bridges the gap between hotels and hostels by combining affordable luxury rooms and smartly designed private bunk beds.
We converted two monumental churches into meeting places for travellers, locals and artists alike. We host inclusive social events in our sustainable restaurant and other communal spaces.

We aim to redefine hospitality by creating a place for communal wonderment. Where those who wander will start to wonder, triggered by true art, honest food and sincere smiles. We make comfort and design available to everyone, without the need for deep pockets. BUNK is where you can feel free to be your wonderfully weird self as you play your part in new stories you can take home with you.

De Vondelbuurt
De Vondelbuurt is een luxe buurt in stadsdeel Amsterdam-West, en heeft veel te bieden. Zo kun je makkelijk een wandeling maken in het Vondelpark, sporten in een van de sportscholen of lekker uitgaan in een van de vele restaurants, cafés of nachtclubs. De Vondelbuurt heeft het allemaal!

Geschiedenis van de Vondelbuurt
Opening van het Vondelpark
In 1865 werd het Vondelpark geopend, en dit was het begin van de Vondelbuurt. Het park werd namelijk aangelegd om de waarde van de toekomstige omliggende huizen te verhogen.

De Vondelbuurt was toen nog een relatief kleine buurt. In de Tweede Wereldoorlog namen de Duitsers het Vondelpark in beslag, en werden diverse delen van de omliggende wijk vernietigd. Na de oorlog, in 1953, kwam het Vondelpark in bezit van de Gemeente Amsterdam.

Het middelpunt van de buurt is het Zonneplein waar het gemeenschapsgebouw Het Zonnehuis een centrale plek inneemt. Het van oorsprong semi-permanente dorp was in eerste instantie bestemd voor arbeidersgezinnen afkomstig uit de verkrotte binnenstad.

De realisatie van de wijk hield verband met de behoefte aan arbeiderskrachten voor de zware scheepsindustrie te bewerkstelligen. In het begin van de twintigste eeuw vestigden zich namelijk steeds meer ondernemingen in Amsterdam Noord. De groeiende werkgelegenheid in dit deel van de stad moest gevoed worden, maar woongelegenheid was er onvoldoende. neighborhood_overview:
Cocomama has quite an interesting history. Believe it or not, but before we turned it into the city's first (and only) boutique hostel, it used to be a well-known brothel. We kept the marble entrance, royal round staircase, original chandeliers and high ceilings in place – the rest we let go of (sorry guys).

We're only one block away from the Albert Cuyp market, Europe's largest daily open-air market. We (and our wallets) love the stalls – offering anything from fresh produce, Dutch street-food, to the latest in fashion (well girls, not sure about the last one, but it's definitely fun to have a look around).

Tram-stop, supermarket, museums, cafés, restaurants, canals, park – anything one needs when visiting Amsterdam is on a stone's throw away. It's as central and easy as it gets.

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.82 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The Nieuwmarkt-area is one of the oldest in Amsterdam, where Jewish and Chinese cultures left their cultural marks and where commerce thrived, symbolised by the former castle-like weighing station of 'De Waag', right in its centre. There are markets and activities almost every day. The area offers a lot of cafés and restaurants. On the west side you'll find the old seamen's area 'De Wallen', better known as the 'Red Light District', on the east side are the small and quiet streets of the 'Lastage' area, home to shipping warfs and warehouses centuries ago.
The Nieuwmarkt area has an active political history, where tension rose high in the late seventies, as protest was fierce when hundreds of houses were demolished to make way for the new subway line, running right under our house.

host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel Amsterdam is a place where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

neighborhood_overview:
The best neighborhood of the Netherlands:

Museumplein district is known as the best neighborhood of Amsterdam, located in Amsterdam Old-South. Van Gogh Museum, Rijks Museum, Concertgebouw, and Vondelpark are within a couple of minutes walking distance. 10 minutes walking, and you'll be at the Leidseplein, the main area for dinner, drinks, and dancing. 15 to 20 minutes walking, and you'll be at the largest conference center, called the RAI.

Sézane's Lodges is located in Amsterdam Old-South, the best neighborhood of the city, perhaps of the Netherlands, 20 seconds away from the Museumplein, and the famous concert hall, called Het Concertgebouw.

Five to ten minutes walking, and you'll be at the Leidseplein, in the center of Amsterdam. There, you'll find all shops, restaurants, cafés, clubs, theaters, and so on you'll be looking for, including the Hardrock Café, American Café, the Stadsschouwburg, and the Melkweg music hall.

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.68 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
The Pijp is located directly south of Amsterdam's city centre and it is part of the borough 'Amsterdam-Zuid'. Most street names in the Pijp are named after famous Dutch painters.
The most famous and busiest street market of the Netherlands, the Albert Cuyp Market, is in the Pijp. It is open six days per week and attracts a lot of tourists. The former Heineken brewery is also a popular tourist attraction. Next to the former Heineken brewery is the Marie Heinekenplein, which has a lot of bars and cafes, as well as the near Gerard Douplein.
It used to be Piet Mondriaan's neighborhood back in the day. And many call it the Quartier Latin of Amsterdam for its great vibe and livelyhood.

name: Boutique hotel in Amsterdam · ★4.53 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Oud-Zuid is the best-kept secret in Amsterdam. And we're giving you the scoop. Bordering the historic center, this trendy neighborhood has the ideal combination of upscale boutiques and memorable museums. Spend your day relaxing in the beautiful greenery of Vondelpark, listening to music spilling from the open-air theater. Or stroll down charming tree-lined streets to admire the stunning 19th-century mansions. Ready for some shopping? Check out P.C. Hooftstraat. Formally named after a Dutch poet and playwright, this luxurious street is home to countless designer stores including Gucci and Dior. After a day of discovery, indulge in one of the many global restaurants and cuisines scattered throughout.

neighborhood_overview: Traditionally a blue collar neighbourhood just a stone's throw away from the heart of town, 'De Baarsjes', is what one calls 'on the rise'. All around us we see new initiatives popping up; from intimate coffee bars and restaurants, to cool boutiques with local designers. Please ask the staff for inside info on where to go!
host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel Amsterdam is a place where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.
property_type: Private room in bed and breakfast

name: Boutique hotel in Amsterdam · ★4.78 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 private bath
neighborhood_overview:
Tucked into Amsterdam's urban fabric, located on the Kloveniersburgwal Rosalia’s menagerie offers the city at your doorstep.

You will find the Nieuwmarkt square and Chinatown to the North, the University of Amsterdam and Amstel river to the South, the old Jewish Quarter to the East and the Dam and Red Light District to the West.

Rosalia's Menagerie is the perfect spot for anyone wanting to be in the center of the best Amsterdam has to offer regarding restaurants, cafes, museums, design, shopping and everything else. We are proud to be located on one of Amsterdam's older canals dating from the late 1400's.
host_about:
Rosalia's Menagerie is a lovely little hideaway located on the Kloveniersgburwal, close to the picturesque Nieuwmarkt Square, in the heart of the historic city centre of Amsterdam. We are proud to be located on one of Amsterdam's oldest canals dating from the late 1400's.

This modernized 17th-century canal house features six personally styled rooms and a world class cocktail bar. Each a unique mix of style, charm and practicality, overlooking either the canal or a fetching Amsterdam secret court yard garden. We offer exceptional hospitality for the cultural pilgrim, the hopeless romantic and weary business traveler alike.

Rosalia's Menagerie is a unique canal house with appealing rooms and a world class cocktail bar that becomes a home in Amsterdam for our guests.

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.87 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
During the 'Golden Century', a gold bank stood right at the center of Amsterdam. Behind this bank once was an alley. After the Tulip-boom the bank went bankrupt and had to break up the land the alley once was and sold it separately. At one side a little house was erected with room for a small shop at the ground floor and tree floors of living space on top. For over a century it was used in this way. But, after refurbishing it to today standards, the two top floors are now available for rent!

Located 5 min from: Dam, Anne Frank House, Jordan Area, Red Light District, 9 streets, trams to all directions.

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★4.80 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Neigborhoud
Hoofddorppleinbuurt is een van de meest authentieke buurten van Amsterdam. Er zijn veel lokale winkels, restaurants en ligt bij Vondelpark. Als je van kleine authentieke, lokale en delicatesse winkels houdt, zul je de buurt geweldig vinden.

Op het plein vind je nutshop, slager, kaaswinkel, bakker en een aantal typische lokale lunch-/dinerkamers (goed voor niet dure koffie, lunch, diner).

Aan de Zeilstraat vind je lokale cadeauwinkels, wilde vlees slager, eco-shop en aan de Amstelveenseweg naar links vind je Fish shop en als je verder weg meer restaurants, een zeer goede bakker en Italiaanse afhaalmaaltijden), tot Vondelpark.


Vervoer
De tram 2 'Centraal station' op het Hoofddorpplein brengt je naar het Museumplein, het Leidseplein en het Centraal station.

Je kunt ook een fiets huren bij M&C BUDGETFIETSEN (je kunt het zien vanuit het huis), of Zeilstraat winkel "huur een fiets".

neighborhood_overview:
Welcome to my neighborhood- De Pijp (The Pipe), one of the city’s most hip and trendy areas, bursting with cozy cafes, diverse restaurants and a lively nightlife.

De Pijp is the home of Heineken. Get to know the famous international beer brand through an interactive guided tour at the Heineken Experience. If you’re searching for a fun family activity, visit Kinderboerderij de Pijp, a children’s petting zoo.

Bohemian De Pijp's narrow streets are lined with Middle Eastern eateries, old-school pubs and cafes with sidewalk terraces. Gregarious stallholders at Albert Cuypmarkt sell Dutch specialties like herrings and waffles.

De Pijp is a foodie’s paradise. The neighborhood is home to almost 150 nationalities and the food choices certainly reflect this diversity. Visitors will find a vast variety of authentic and exotic ethnic cuisine, such as Syrian, Moroccan, Surinamese, Turkish, Japanese, Spanish and more. Bar-ca takes you to Spain, while vegetarians fi

We are conscious about the choices we make. That is why there is sustainability in everything that we do, without compromising comfort. And our stylish hotels and restaurants each have their own unique style and story, which makes every visit a special experience. We do it differently by nature.

We have been around for over 10 years now, making us pioneers in eco-friendly tourism.

We do it differently by combining stylish design and playfulness with sustainability, calling it Eco-Sexy. This is felt throughout your entire stay. From small notes in the rooms that tell guests about the recycled furniture and water-saving showers to every bite and drink that are served being fully organic. There is no stopping us delivering the eco choice while maintaining a high level of comfort.

In the Jordaan, there are several markets you can visit. Every Monday, there is a flea market at the Noordermarkt. It is the perfect spot to buy Dutch plates, pots and linen. They are also selling clothes and accessories. For a foodmarket, you can go to the Lindenmarkt at the Lindengracht on Saturdays, to the Westerstraat market on Mondays or to the Biological foodmarket at the Noordermarkt on Saturdays.

The Westertoren is one of the landmarks of the Jordaan. It's really worth to visit and climb! Also close by: Anne Frank Huis, Dam, Royal Palace.

Nice to know: each of the streets is named after a flower.
host_about:
Kith & Kin is a brand-new boutique apartment hotel in the heart of Amsterdam. We welcome you to stay for any length of time in one of our four self-catering apartments, that combine the comfort of home with the style and service of a boutique hotel. 

Who we are: best friends, both mother of two girls (also best friends) and of a boy, Amsterdam residents for over 20 years, Airbnb hosts from the beginning, entrepreneurs, design lovers, working in creative industrie and now owner of Kith & Kin Hotel. Located in a quiet residential area, between the authentic Jordaan and the up-and-coming West area; a new bustling melting pot of great shops, restaurants and bars. Our insider tips into local city life, invite you to experience Amsterdam like a local and feel instantly at home.
Thank you, Jelleke & Cathelijne

name: Rental unit in Amsterdam · ★5.0 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: In terms of design and development, De Baarsjes is like Oud West: densely populated with few green spaces, but lots of wide streets, squares and facilities. In the 1990s, many neglected buildings were refurbished or replaced by new construction. Mercatorplein was extensively renovated and is the only square completely designed by Berlage that still exists in Amsterdam, thanks to a campaign by residents, which ensured that nothing was demolished. Oud West was a higher priority than De Baarsjes in terms of redevelopment, so De Baarsjes is still lagging in social development by comparison. Even so, it remains a popular neighbourhood with many satisfied residents.

neighborhood_overview:

Also we have a great Thai restaurant (Me nam naan, Koningsstraat) across the street. Otherwise you have dinner with the kids in the relaxed garden of Café van Beeren 1 minute away. During day time you can walk to Artis Zoo, play in the fountains next to it and have a drink at Restaurant Plantage. The kids can paddle on the roof of NEMO Science Center while you drink a cold beer. Or you rent a bike and take the ferry at Amsterdam Centraal to the northern part of the city to discover the beautiful Dutch countryside.

name: Home in Amsterdam · ★4.67 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Recht in het hart van de populaire Jordaan ligt tussen de Bloemgracht en de Egelantiersgracht de Nieuwe Leliestraat. Het appartement ligt vrijwel aan het einde van de straat waar deze eindigt tegen de Lijnbaansgracht. Waterrijk Amsterdam; vanuit het appartement is er zicht op de historische grachten. De gezellige Rozengracht met alle winkels voor dagelijkse en niet-dagelijkse benodigdheden ligt binnen handbereik. Het Anne Frankhuis met de prachtige Westerkerk en de 9 straatjes liggen op minder dan 5 minuten lopen. Door de ideale ligging van de Jordaan zijn het Leidseplein en het Centraal Station nog geen 500 meter verwijderd!

Ruim 130 jaar geleden aangelegd als wijk voor de Amsterdamse arbeiders, is de Jordaan al ruim 15 jaar een van de meest gewilde locaties. De goede bereikbaarheid, het hoge voorzieningsniveau en de gezelligheid van deze buurt zijn hiervoor de belangrijkste verklaringen.

Bereikbaarheid: Tramlijnen 5, 13 en 17 zijn in de directe nabijheid gelegen

neighborhood_overview:
The Leidse Square and Amsterdam canals are nothing but highlights. Throughout the world-famous canals maze-like streets offer hidden courtyards. Originally a working-class neighbourhood, this district has become one of the most expensive, upscale locations in the Netherlands. It is home to many art galleries and is also dotted with speciality shops and restaurants. Tons of nice restaurants and clubs (Salmuera, Palladium, Jimmy Woo, Sea Food bar, Chin Chin Club). Within a three-min walking distance from Museum Square, the Van Gogh Museum and the Vondelpark

Around ten-min walking distance you’re in the Amsterdam Jordaan where you will find the Anne Frank house, the Wester Church, the Dam Square and the famous Noordermarkt (biological food market each Saturday and textile market each Monday).

Around twelve-min walking you’re in the popular Amsterdam de Pijp with lot’s of restaurants/bars and the Heineken Brewery!

Enjoy the little design boutiques with fur

neighborhood_overview: Traditionally a blue collar neighbourhood just a stone's throw away from the heart of town, 'De Baarsjes', is what one calls 'on the rise'. All around us we see new initiatives popping up; from intimate coffee bars and restaurants, to cool boutiques with local designers. Please ask the staff for inside info on where to go!
host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel Amsterdam is a place where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

name: Home in Amsterdam · ★4.84 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 private bath
neighborhood_overview: Our neighbourhood (and especially our dead-end street) have an exceptional village feel to them. The canal that connects to the countryside to the North add to the typical North-Holland ambiance. Nature reserves Twiske and Ilperveld, as well as Waterland and world-famous Zaanse Schans, are just around the corner. On the other hand, you can reach the center of Amsterdam in under 20 minutes, either by bus or on your rental bicycle (riding the free ferry over the IJ just adds to the joy of living in North).
host_about:
I love making music, gardening, riding my bicycle and turning my house into a beautiful and cozy space. Together with my husband Jang, I love to receive guests and sharing all that makes our spot such a wonderful place to live in. I love the colours in and around our house.

I teach music to very young children (I used to be a kindergarten teacher) and was able to turn my music hobby into my profession. I love classical pieces, but also folk and world music. We love visiting small music festivals, especially in summer.

When I stop moving around and take the time to sit down and read, I usually pick up a psychological novel. We try to minimize watching TV, but if we do watch it, we choose travel and housefinding programmes. Going to a movie with a friend is another one of my regular treats.

We eat food from various foreign cultures, such as Turkish, Indonesian, Mexican, Libanese, Thai, etc. Of course we also love to travel, together or on our own. Portugal, Czech Republic, France, Norway, Turkey, America, Aruba, Lebanon, Syria, South-Africa. These are some of the countries we have visited. Ik like camping as well as staying in a bed and breakfast. A hotel is fine for a couple of nights, but not my favourite stay on a holiday trip. I like to travel by train or bicycle.

My life's motto would be: sharing my good fortune and happiness with others.

Hey there! 

Great that you are having a look at my personal profile. 

In short something about myself; I work and live in Amsterdam since 2009. During work days I have to go right through the city center on my bike to get from “de Pijp”  (the area I live) to the office next to Central Station. In Amsterdam you never get bored with all the entertainment / shopping area’s, musea, and great terraces with the canal sceneries on the background.

In addition, the city allows me to variate on the restaurants I like to go to, to meet up with friends and relax in its surrounding nature.  As I like to exercise 3 to 4 times a week it is great  to have the Sarphati park next door and greater green areas just outside the city center. 

Conclusion, I thoroughly enjoy living in Amsterdam and would highly recommend it for both business and/ or pleasure.

neighborhood_overview: The famous Jordaan neighbourhood is a former working-class bastion, renowned for tight community bonds, radical politics and a love for drink and over-the-top sing-a-longs. Gentrification of decades past has attracted more galleries, restaurants, concept stores and vintage boutiques to its flowery streets, but there is undeniably still a distinct atmosphere to enjoy here. Discover lively café terraces, historic brown bars, the bustling Noordermarkt, elm-lined canal streets, quirky museums and of course, the Anne Frank House.

A short cycle east of the city centre, Nieuwe Kerkstraat sits within the desirable Plantage district. Famous for its elegant squares and leafy boulevards, Amsterdam’s ‘cultural garden’ is packed with theatres, galleries, museums and parks, yet conveniently close to the thriving business district.

For your comfort, towels, bed linen and a weekly housekeeping are provided. Some apartments also feature a washing machine and there are public laundry rooms. The Hermitage Museum is just 650 meters away, while Artis Zoo is only 400 meters from Wittenberg by Cove. The nearest airport is Schiphol Airport, 12 km away or a 30-minute drive by car.
